   <h1>Re: Would you?</h1>
   <b>&quot;Russell Barr&quot; &lt;guzziot_at_localaccess_dot_com&gt;</b><br/>
   <i>1999-02-23 16:22:08+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>I think the going rate for a good late westy is in the 4k-buck range.  If
you add the cost of the new head or heads that this one seems to need them
to $3000, you're lookin' at about fair market value.

Correct me if I'm wrong on this folks.  I had a neighbor drop by with his
really nice '78 Westy and ask me what he thought he could get for it.  It
had recent heads, but also had a rust hole clean through the outer shell
under the windshield.  No floor rust, just that nasty bit under the
windshield.  Which is about the equivalent of a head job in cost (IMHO), at
least if it's fixed right.  I told I'd give him $2500 for it, if I was in
the market.
Just my .02

Russell
'69 Riviera daily driver
'78 Project kid hauler
'77 donor
'71 donor
I can quit buying busses anytime I want

> Hi All,
> I'm contemplating the purchase of a 1978 Westy. The owner is a friend of
> mine who bought it a few years ago and drove it some 5400 miles in one
big
> stint and then parked it. No rust, new paint, new canvas pop top, just
had
> it smogged in CA. He's asking $3000 for it.
> 
> Here's the snag it has this curious habit of consuming oil. To be clear
it
> doesn't SEEM to burn oil (doesn't blow smoke, doesn't even leak when
> parked). It just eats a quart or so every 300-500 miles.
> 
> It's had this nasty proclivity since my friend acquired it. As he was
> driving all over the country at the time it made him a bit nervous at
> first. En route he took it to three different mechanics who couldn't
really
> figure it out. He says a VW guru in Moab CO told him just to keep putting
> oil in it. Said he'd seen this kind of thing before. Suggested that
putting
> in really heavy weight oil might solve the problem. As my friend was on
the
> last leg of his tour he never got around to trying this suggestion.
> 
> Considering these facts is $3000 a reasonable price? The Bus is really
> clean, runs well, original plaid upholstery. Doesn't have the stove/frig
> package though just sink.
> 
> Should I kill the deal on principal over the mystery of the disappearing
> oil? Worst case what's the going  rate on a rebuilt motor.
> 
> Final consideration I have to travel from Colorado to California to pick
up
> the beastie.
> 
> Give it to me straight. I can take it.
> 
> Regards,
> 
> Ian
> Boulder Colorado
> Non Bus owner at present
> (Did have a 69 convertible Ghia in College)
> 
> 
> Ian Himell
> New Millennium Communications, Inc.
> 303-444-1476 Ph.
> 303-444-1136 Fax
> ian_at_nmci_dot_com
> </pre>


